<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-04-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-04-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="208" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d208">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/255: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-04-25"><hi rend="italic">April 25, 1928</hi>—(?) <hi rend="italic">p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 25—11
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>271. A report dated April 16th from Vice Consul Paxton quotes from
                            letters from a considerable number of missionaries in Kiangsu and Anhwei
                            indicating that, in general, missionaries who have returned to their
                            stations have found diminution in antiforeign attitude on the part of
                            both civilians and troops but that in spite of this and assurances given
                            by Nanking government the greater part of American buildings are still
                            occupied by the military.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
